Title:
Bypassing detections with command-line obfuscation

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
This post explains how EDR/AV detections that rely on process command-line strings can be bypassed by generating semantically equivalent but syntactically altered arguments. It distinguishes “command-line obfuscation” (target executable parsing quirks; obfuscation persists into EDR telemetry) from shell-level obfuscation like DOSfuscation/PowerShell obfuscation (often resolves before telemetry). The author surveys many obfuscation primitives across Windows and *nix (e.g., option character substitution, Unicode homoglyphs, quote insertion, path/URL manipulation, value transformations) and shows how they break common Sigma/Splunk/Elastic rules. A methodology is presented to systematically test executables for obfuscation tolerance using automated equivalence checking (exit code/stdout) and to encode findings as machine-readable “model files.” Results for 68 Windows 11 LOLBINs are published via ArgFuscator.net and open-source tooling (Invoke-ArgFuscator) to generate randomized obfuscated command lines. It’s useful for red teams to evaluate detection gaps and for defenders to harden detections via normalization, anomaly heuristics, and shifting to less-spoofable telemetry (e.g., network events vs. CLI substrings).

Technical Focus:
- Command-line parsing ambiguities and argv/argument tokenization
- LOLBIN/“malwareless” tradecraft and process creation telemetry evasion
- Obfuscation techniques: Unicode substitution/insertion, quote stuffing, option rewriting, path/URL/value transformations
- Automated differential testing for command equivalence (exit code/stdout)
- Detection engineering: normalization (e.g., MDE parse_command_line), anomaly-based heuristics, resilient rule design

Use Cases:
- Generate synonymous obfuscated commands to test EDR/SIEM process-creation detections
- Build regression tests for detection content against known obfuscation variants
- Create/extend obfuscation models for additional executables and environments
- Develop defensive normalization and anomaly detections for suspicious CLI patterns
- Validate whether detections should pivot from CLI strings to behavioral telemetry (network, file, registry)

Keywords:
command-line obfuscation, argv, process creation telemetry, EDR evasion, AV bypass, LOLBIN, living-off-the-land, Windows 11 23H2, Sigma rules, Splunk detections, Elastic detection rules, Unicode homoglyphs, quote insertion, option character substitution, argument normalization, Microsoft Defender for Endpoint, parse_command_line, ArgFuscator.net, Invoke-ArgFuscator, certutil, reg.exe, msiexec, mshta, MITRE ATT&CK T1027.010